\app~uses call graph to represent the anomaly propagation in microservice environments.
As shown in Figure \ref{fig:overview}, our call graph consists of a set of services nodes S = {S_{1},S_{2},...,S_{k}}.
For each service node S_{i}, we add edges to all other service S_{j} it communicates with.
We also record the system metrics generated by the calls between services on the edges, i.e., EC, RT, QPS.
For example, the response time on the edge of S_{i} calls S_{j} represents the average response time per second between services per minute.

The construction of call graph needs to collect the call relationships data between microservices and related system metrics, we mainly collect these two kinds of data through EagleEye \cite{EagleEye}.
EagleEye is a distribute trace monitoring system developed by Alibaba, it mainly consists of four modules: trace data generation SDK; real-time ETL data processing system; offline computing cluster and web-based user interface, it records information such as the invocation process and response time between services.
However, it provides microservice instance-level invocation data and second-level system metrics, such as the average response time per second between microservice instance S_{1} and S_{2}.

For anomaly detection performance considerations, we aggregate microservice instance-level data and second-level system metrics data to microservice-level and minute-level.
For example, a microservices S_{1} may have multiple instance{S_{1}_{1},S_{1}_{2},...S_{1}_{k}}, through aggregation, there is only one node S_{1} on the graph.
For metrics data, we aggregate metrics data at the second-level to the minute-level, for example, response time represents the average response time per second between microservice instances, we get the average response time per second per minute between microservice-level services by aggregation.
The reason for this is because there are too many metrics are collected in the second-level metrics, which will reduce the performance of anomaly detection; and after observation, it is found that the jitter of the second-level indicator is relatively large, and it is easy to misreport during anomaly detection.

For all the data on the graph, we use the time series database to save.
